		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.heartlightministries.org/blogs/pttradio/?p=6472</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Do you struggle with what your teen is sharing online?]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<small>(Click title to listen)</small><br /><p>PODCAST SCRIPT:</p>
<p>Turn on the news station, watch YouTube videos, browse Facebook… everyone desperately wants to be heard!</p>
<p>It’s not bad to have an opinion.  But for teens, there are two volatile elements:  the invitation to publically express personal opinion, and the immaturity and irresponsibility they’re still growing out of.  Combine those two things and what do you get?  A recipe for disaster and broken friendships!</p>
<p>You see, when a teen is allowed to share opinions publically, it often morphs into mockery of others, judgmental statements or just plain ol’ meanness.  Then, with the click of a mouse, those hurtful statements are broadcast to the digital world.</p>
<p>Mom and dad… pay careful attention to the opinions your teen is sharing in a digital age!</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<hr style="border-top:black solid 1px" /><small>©2012 Mark Gregston www.parentingtodaysteens.org. Email: markgregston@heartlightministries.org.  Phone: 1-866-700-3264<br /><br />Also, listen via iTunes <a href="http://itunes.apple.com/podcast/parenting-todays-teens/id337635368">here</a>.</small><br />]]></content:encoded>
