		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.heartlightministries.org/blogs/pttradio/?p=6461</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[What are some conversation starters that you use?]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<small>(Click title to listen)</small><br /><p>PODCAST SCRIPT:</p>
<p>I meet too many moms and dads who are frustrated by their teen’s lack of communication.  The only thing they ever get is a grunt or a one-word answer.</p>
<div>Maybe that’s the case in your home, too.  So, start asking open- ended questions… just for the heck of it.  Don’t jump in with the answer, and don’t belittle your kid if they have a wacky response.  Try it out.  Ask your teen things like …</div>
<div><em><br />
</em></div>
<div><em>What’s one thing you’d want to change about our family?</em>… or …<em>Who’s the greatest sports hero of all time?</em>… or …<em>When was the last time you laughed out loud and why?  </em>Have some fun with it.  You might be surprised by the responses they blurt out … when you engage them in conversation.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<hr style="border-top:black solid 1px" /><small>©2012 Mark Gregston www.parentingtodaysteens.org. Email: markgregston@heartlightministries.org.  Phone: 1-866-700-3264<br /><br />Also, listen via iTunes <a href="http://itunes.apple.com/podcast/parenting-todays-teens/id337635368">here</a>.</small><br />]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://www.heartlightministries.org/blogs/pttradio/2012/06/04/conversation-starters-6042012/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
<enclosure url="http://www.heartlightftp.com/radio/Web/PTT/ptt20120604.mp3" length="944613" type="audio/mpeg" />
	<itunes:summary>(Click title to listen)PODCAST SCRIPT:
I meet too many moms and dads who are frustrated by their teen’s lack of communication.  The only thing they ever get is a grunt or a one-word answer.
Maybe that’s the case in your home, too.  So, start asking open- ended questions… just for the heck of it.  Don’t jump in with the answer, and don’t belittle your kid if they have a wacky response.  Try it out.  Ask your teen things like …


What’s one thing you’d want to change about our family?… or …Who’s the greatest sports hero of all time?… or …When was the last time you laughed out loud and why?  Have some fun with it.  You might be surprised by the responses they blurt out … when you engage them in conversation.
 

©2012 Mark Gregston www.parentingtodaysteens.org. Email: markgregston@heartlightministries.org.  Phone: 1-866-700-3264Also, listen via iTunes here.</itunes:summary>
